+# Harness Agent Runtime
+
+Ordinary saved-agent conversations use Microsoft Agent Framework `HarnessAgent` as their only runtime implementation.
+
+## Runtime shape
+
+```text
+Saved Agent Definition
+        ↓
+HarnessAgentFactory
+        ↓
+HarnessAgent + AgentSession
+        ↓
+UnifiedAgentRuntimeChatSessionService
+        ↓
+AppChat UI transcript
+```
+
+A saved agent remains a declarative definition: identity, instructions, model selection, model settings, MCP bindings, application tools, and execution settings. `HarnessAgentFactory` resolves that definition into a `HarnessAgent` directly from `IChatClient`.
+
+The factory does not create an `AgentSession`. A session belongs to a particular conversation lifecycle.
+
+## Direct chat lifecycle
+
+`UnifiedAgentRuntimeChatSessionService` owns one `HarnessAgent` and one `AgentSession` for the current direct conversation.
+
+- Starting a new chat materializes the agent and calls `CreateSessionAsync` once.
+- Sending a message passes only the new user message to `RunStreamingAsync` together with the existing session.
+- The UI transcript is updated from streaming framework events, but it is never converted back into agent history.
+- Reset discards the agent, session, cancellation source, streaming state, and transcript, then starts a fresh conversation.
+- Changing the saved agent, model, MCP bindings, tools, or execution settings starts a new conversation and therefore a new session.
+- Cancel completes the visible streaming placeholder and leaves the UI idle. A canceled direct session is not rebuilt from the transcript; the user starts a new chat before continuing.
+
+The `AgentSession` is the source of truth for agent history and provider state. `AppChat` is only a presentation model for visible messages, attachments, errors, streaming state, and export.
+
+## Harness defaults used by ordinary chat
+
+Ordinary chat must remain useful for simple questions, so the application explicitly disables Harness capabilities that would otherwise change every prompt into an autonomous task:
+
+- todo provider;
+- plan/execute mode provider;
+- file memory;
+- skills discovery;
+- hosted web search;
+- default Harness working-style instructions.
+
+Tools configured by the saved agent remain available. Harness owns the single function-invocation loop. Retry, timeout, logging, MCP interaction scope, and call recording are implemented around individual tools rather than around the agent.
+
+Compaction and function-loop limits are expressed through `HarnessAgentOptions`; the removed application-specific compaction and invocation pipelines are not used.
+
+## RAG
+
+RAG is integrated through `AgenticRagContextProvider`. Retrieval is performed for the current user request and supplied as transient runtime context. Retrieved text is not inserted into the UI transcript and is not treated as a user or assistant message.
+
+## Workflow lifecycle
+
+Workflow execution continues to use the shared workflow runtime and `AgentRunEvent` protocol. When a saved agent is used as a workflow participant, it is materialized by the same `IHarnessAgentFactory` and receives a temporary `AgentSession` for that invocation.
+
+Workflow and participant sessions are not persisted. A workflow run creates its runtime, executes, projects its visible transcript, and releases the runtime after completion.
+
+The difference between direct chat and workflow is lifecycle, not agent type:
+
+```text
+Direct chat → HarnessAgent → long-lived session for the active conversation
+Workflow    → HarnessAgent participant → temporary session for one invocation
+```
+
+## Persistence and export
+
+Saved agent definitions and saved workflow definitions remain persistent. User chat sessions are not persisted and old saved chats are not loaded or migrated.
+
+The current visible transcript can be copied or exported as text, Markdown, or HTML. Export does not include serialized sessions, system prompts, provider state, hidden RAG context, or secrets.
+
+## Deferred Harness capabilities
+
+Approvals, todo visualization, explicit plan/execute modes, writable workspaces, file editing, code execution, skills discovery, hosted web search, background agents, artifacts, durable workflow state, and persistent `AgentSession` serialization are intentionally deferred.
